# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: closure-conversion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] In computer science, a **call stack** is a stack data structure that stores information about the active subroutines and inline blocks of a computer program.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] This type of stack is also known as an **execution stack**, **program stack**, **control stack**, **run-time stack**, or **machine stack**, and is often shortened to simply the "**stack**".
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Although maintenance of the call stack is important for the proper functioning of most software, the details are normally hidden and automatic in high-level programming languages.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Many computer instruction sets provide special instructions for manipulating stacks.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] A call stack is used for several related purposes, but the main reason for having one is to keep track of the point to which each active subroutine should return control when it finishes executing.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] An active subroutine is one that has been called, but is yet to complete execution, after which control should be handed back to the point of call.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Such activations of subroutines may be nested to any level (recursive as a special case), hence the stack structure.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] For example, if a subroutine `DrawSquare` calls a subroutine `DrawLine` from four different places, `DrawLine` must know where to return when its execution completes.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] To accomplish this, the address following the instruction that jumps to `DrawLine`, the *return address*, is pushed onto the top of the call stack as part of each call.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] If a called subroutine calls on yet another subroutine, it will push another return address onto the call stack, and so on, with the information stacking up and unstacking as the program dictates.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] If the pushing consumes all of the space allocated for the call stack, an error called a stack overflow occurs, generally causing the program to crash.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Adding a block's or subroutine's entry to the call stack is sometimes called "winding", and removing entries "unwinding".
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] There is usually exactly one call stack associated with a running program (or more accurately, with each task or thread of a process), although additional stacks may be created for signal handling or cooperative multitasking (as with setcontext).
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Since there is only one in this important context, it can be referred to as *the* stack (implicitly "of the task"); however, in the Forth programming language the *data stack* or *parameter stack* is accessed more explicitly than the call stack and is commonly referred to as *the* stack (see below).
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] In high-level programming languages, the specifics of the call stack are usually hidden from the programmer.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] They are given access only to a set of functions, and not the memory on the stack itself.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Most assembly languages, on the other hand, require programmers to be involved in manipulating the stack.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The actual details of the stack in a programming language depend upon the compiler, operating system, and the available instruction set.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] As noted above, the primary purpose of a call stack is to *store the return addresses*.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] When a subroutine is called, the location (address) of the instruction at which the calling routine can later resume must be saved somewhere.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Using a stack to save the return address has important advantages over some alternative calling conventions, such as saving the return address before the beginning of the called subroutine or in some other fixed location.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] One is that each task can have its own stack, and thus the subroutine can be thread-safe, that is, able to be active simultaneously for different tasks doing different things.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Another benefit is that by providing reentrancy, recursion is automatically supported.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] When a function calls itself recursively, a return address needs to be stored for each activation of the function so that it can later be used to return from the function activation.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Stack structures provide this capability automatically.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] , the variables that are known only within the active subroutine and do not retain values after it returns.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] It is often convenient to allocate space for this use by simply moving the top of the stack by enough to provide the space.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Note that each separate activation of a subroutine gets its own separate space in the stack for locals.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] may allocate a stack frame for local variables.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] As with a call frame, the values are lost when the block exits.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] be supplied to them by the code which calls them, and it is not uncommon that space for these parameters may be laid out in the call stack.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] will be used to pass the values, but if there are more parameters than can be handled this way, memory space will be needed.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The call stack works well as a place for these parameters, especially since each call to a subroutine, which will have differing values for parameters, will be given separate space on the call stack for those values.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Operands for arithmetic or logical operations are most often placed into registers and operated on there.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] , is called an evaluation stack, and may occupy space in the call stack.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] , which are allowed to access the context of their enclosing routines, i.e., the parameters and local variables within the scope of the outer routines.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Such static nesting can repeat (a function declared within a function declared within a function…).
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The implementation must provide a means by which a called function at any given static nesting level can reference the enclosing frame at each enclosing nesting level.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] which is indexed to locate a desired frame.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The depth of a routine's lexical nesting is a known constant, so the size of a routine's display is fixed.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Also, the number of containing scopes to traverse is known, the index into the display is also fixed.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] implemented such a display in hardware which supported up to 32 levels of static nesting.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The display entries denoting containing scopes are obtained from the appropriate prefix of the caller's display.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] An inner routine which recurses creates separate call frames for each invocation.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] In this case, all of the inner routine's static links point to the same outer routine context.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] , a block within a procedure may have its own local variables, allocated on block entry and freed on block exit.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Similarly, the block may have its own exception handlers, deactivated at block exit.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Beside the return address, in some environments there may be other machine or software states that need to be restored when a subroutine returns.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] This might include things like privilege level, exception-handling information, arithmetic modes, and so on.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] If needed, this may be stored in the call stack just as the return address is.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The typical call stack is used for the return address, locals, and parameters (known as a *call frame*).
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] In some environments there may be more or fewer functions assigned to the call stack.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Some Forths also have a third stack for floating-point parameters.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] A call stack is composed of **stack frames** (also called *activation records* or *activation frames*).
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] These are machine dependent and ABI-dependent data structures containing subroutine state information.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Each stack frame corresponds to an invocation of a subroutine that has not yet completed with a return.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The stack frame at the top of the stack is for the currently executing routine.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] For example, if a subroutine named `DrawLine` is currently running, having been called by a subroutine `DrawSquare`, the top part of the call stack might be laid out like in the adjacent picture.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] A diagram like this can be drawn in either direction as long as the placement of the top, and so direction of stack growth, is understood.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Architectures differ as to whether call stacks grow towards higher addresses or towards lower addresses, so the logic of any diagram is not dependent on this addressing choice by convention.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] While it is actively executing, with its frame at the stack top, a routine can access the information within its frame as needed.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] When stack frame sizes can differ, such as between different functions or between invocations of a particular function, popping a frame off the stack does not constitute a fixed decrement of the **stack pointer**.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] At function return, the stack pointer is instead restored to the **frame pointer**, the value of the stack pointer just before the function was called.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Each stack frame contains a frame pointer to the top of the frame immediately below.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The stack pointer is a mutable register shared between all invocations.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] A frame pointer of a given invocation of a function is a copy of the stack pointer as it was before the function was invoked.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The locations of all other fields in the frame can be defined relative either to the top of the frame, as negative offsets of the stack pointer, or relative to the top of the frame below, as positive offsets of the frame pointer.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The location of the frame pointer itself must inherently be defined as a negative offset of the stack pointer.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] In most systems a stack frame has a field to contain the previous value of the frame pointer register, the value it had while the caller was executing.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] For example, the stack frame of `DrawLine` would have a memory location holding the frame pointer value that `DrawSquare` uses (not shown in the diagram above).
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The value is saved upon entry to the subroutine.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Having such a field in a known location in the stack frame enables code to access each frame successively underneath the currently executing routine's frame, and also allows the routine to easily restore the frame pointer to the *caller's* frame, just before it returns.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Programming languages that support nested subroutines also have a field in the call frame that points to the stack frame of the *latest* activation of the procedure that most closely encapsulates the callee, i.e. the immediate *scope* of the callee.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] This is called an *access link* or *static link* (as it keeps track of static nesting during dynamic and recursive calls) and provides the routine (as well as any other routines it may invoke) access to the local data of its encapsulating routines at every nesting level.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Some architectures, compilers, or optimization cases store one link for each enclosing level (not just the immediately enclosing), so that deeply nested routines that access shallow data do not have to traverse several links; this strategy is often called a "display".
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Access links can be optimized away when an inner function does not access any (non-constant) local data in the encapsulation, as is the case with pure functions communicating only via arguments and return values, for example.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] For some purposes, the stack frame of a subroutine and that of its caller can be considered to overlap, the overlap consisting of the area where the parameters are passed from the caller to the callee.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] In some environments, the caller pushes each argument onto the stack, thus extending its stack frame, then invokes the callee.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] In other environments, the caller has a preallocated area at the top of its stack frame to hold the arguments it supplies to other subroutines it calls.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] This area is sometimes termed the *outgoing arguments area* or *callout area*.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Under this approach, the size of the area is calculated by the compiler to be the largest needed by any called subroutine.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Usually the call stack manipulation needed at the site of a call to a subroutine is minimal (which is good since there can be many call sites for each subroutine to be called).
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The values for the actual arguments are evaluated at the call site, since they are specific to the particular call, and either pushed onto the stack or placed into registers, as determined by the used calling convention.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The actual call instruction, such as "branch and link", is then typically executed to transfer control to the code of the target subroutine.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] In the called subroutine, the first code executed is usually termed the subroutine prologue, since it does the necessary housekeeping before the code for the statements of the routine is begun.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Similarly, the current stack pointer and/or frame pointer values may be pushed.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] If frame pointers are being used, the prologue will typically set the new value of the frame pointer register from the stack pointer.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Space on the stack for local variables can then be allocated by incrementally changing the stack pointer.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The Forth programming language allows explicit winding of the call stack (called there the "return stack").
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] When a subroutine is ready to return, it executes an epilogue that undoes the steps of the prologue.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] This will typically restore saved register values (such as the frame pointer value) from the stack frame, pop the entire stack frame off the stack by changing the stack pointer value, and finally branch to the instruction at the return address.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Under many calling conventions, the items popped off the stack by the epilogue include the original argument values, in which case there usually are no further stack manipulations that need to be done by the caller.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] With some calling conventions, however, it is the caller's responsibility to remove the arguments from the stack after the return.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Returning from the called function will pop the top frame off the stack, perhaps leaving a return value.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The more general act of popping one or more frames off the stack to resume execution elsewhere in the program is called **stack unwinding** and must be performed when non-local control structures are used, such as those used for exception handling.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] In this case, the stack frame of a function contains one or more entries specifying exception handlers.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] When an exception is thrown, the stack is unwound until a handler is found that is prepared to handle (catch) the type of the thrown exception.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Some languages have other control structures that require general unwinding.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Pascal allows a global goto statement to transfer control out of a nested function and into a previously invoked outer function.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] This operation requires the stack to be unwound, removing as many stack frames as necessary to restore the proper context to transfer control to the target statement within the enclosing outer function.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Similarly, C has the `setjmp` and `longjmp` functions that act as non-local gotos.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Common Lisp allows control of what happens when the stack is unwound by using the `unwind-protect` special operator.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] When applying a continuation, the stack is (logically) unwound and then rewound with the stack of the continuation.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] This is not the only way to implement continuations; for example, using multiple, explicit stacks, application of a continuation can simply activate its stack and wind a value to be passed.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The Scheme programming language allows arbitrary thunks to be executed in specified points on "unwinding" or "rewinding" of the control stack when a continuation is invoked.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] The call stack can sometimes be inspected as the program is running.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Depending on how the program is written and compiled, the information on the stack can be used to determine intermediate values and function call traces.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] This has been used to generate fine-grained automated tests, and in cases like Ruby and Smalltalk, to implement first-class continuations.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] As an example, the GNU Debugger (GDB) implements interactive inspection of the call stack of a running, but paused, C program.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Taking regular-time samples of the call stack can be useful in profiling the performance of programs as, if a subroutine's address appears in the call stack sampling data many times, it is likely to act as a code bottleneck and should be inspected for performance problems.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] One such attack involves filling one buffer with arbitrary executable code, and then overflowing this or some other buffer to overwrite some return address with a value that points directly to the executable code.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] As a result, when the function returns, the computer executes that code.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] This kind of an attack can be blocked with W^X, but similar attacks can succeed even with W^X protection enabled, including the return-to-libc attack or the attacks coming from return-oriented programming.
[src:closure-conversion/call-stack] Various mitigations have been proposed, such as storing arrays in a completely separate location from the return stack, as is the case in the Forth programming language.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In programming languages, a **closure**, also **lexical closure** or **function closure**, is a technique for implementing lexically scoped name binding in a language with first-class functions.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Operationally, a closure is a record storing a function together with an environment.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The environment is a mapping associating each free variable of the function (variables that are used locally, but defined in an enclosing scope) with the value or reference to which the name was bound when the closure was created.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Unlike a plain function, a closure allows the function to access those *captured variables* through the closure's copies of their values or references, even when the function is invoked outside their scope.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The concept of closures was developed in the 1960s for the mechanical evaluation of expressions in the λ-calculus and was first fully implemented in 1970 as a language feature in the PAL programming language to support lexically scoped first-class functions.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Peter Landin defined the term *closure* in 1964 as having an *environment part* and a *control part* as used by his SECD machine for evaluating expressions.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Joel Moses credits Landin with introducing the term *closure* to refer to a lambda expression with open bindings (free variables) that have been closed by (or bound in) the lexical environment, resulting in a *closed expression*, or closure.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This use was subsequently adopted by Sussman and Steele when they defined Scheme in 1975, a lexically scoped variant of Lisp, and became widespread.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Sussman and Abelson also use the term *closure* in the 1980s with a second, unrelated meaning: the property of an operator that adds data to a data structure to also be able to add nested data structures.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This use of the term comes from mathematics use, rather than the prior use in computer science.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] the values of `a` and `b` are closures, in both cases produced by returning a nested function with a free variable from the enclosing function, so that the free variable binds to the value of parameter `x` of the enclosing function.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The closures in `a` and `b` are functionally identical.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The only difference in implementation is that in the first case we used a nested function with a name, `g`, while in the second case we used an anonymous nested function (using the Python keyword `lambda` for creating an anonymous function).
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The original name, if any, used in defining them is irrelevant.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] A closure is a value like any other value.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] It does not need to be assigned to a variable and can instead be used directly, as shown in the last two lines of the example.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This usage may be deemed an "anonymous closure".
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The nested function definitions are not themselves closures: they have a free variable which is not yet bound.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Only once the enclosing function is evaluated with a value for the parameter is the free variable of the nested function bound, creating a closure, which is then returned from the enclosing function.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This is most often achieved by a function return, since the function must be defined within the scope of the non-local variables, in which case typically its own scope will be smaller.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This can also be achieved by variable shadowing (which reduces the scope of the non-local variable), though this is less common in practice, as it is less useful and shadowing is discouraged.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The use of closures is associated with languages where functions are first-class objects, in which functions can be returned as results from higher-order functions, or passed as arguments to other function calls; if functions with free variables are first-class, then returning one creates a closure.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This includes functional programming languages such as Lisp and ML, and many modern, multi-paradigm languages, such as Julia, Python, and Rust.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Closures are also often used with callbacks, particularly for event handlers, such as in JavaScript, where they are used for interactions with a dynamic web page.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Closures can also be used in a continuation-passing style to hide state.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Constructs such as objects and control structures can thus be implemented with closures.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In some languages, a closure may occur when a function is defined within another function, and the inner function refers to local variables of the outer function.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] At run-time, when the outer function executes, a closure is formed, consisting of the inner function's code and references (the upvalues) to any variables of the outer function required by the closure.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Closures typically appear in languages with first-class functions—in other words, such languages enable functions to be passed as arguments, returned from function calls, bound to variable names, etc., just like simpler types such as strings and integers.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In this example, the lambda expression `(lambda (book) (>= (book-sales book) threshold))` appears within the function `best-selling-books`.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] When the lambda expression is evaluated, Scheme creates a closure consisting of the code for the lambda expression and a reference to the `threshold` variable, which is a free variable inside the lambda expression.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The closure is then passed to the `filter` function, which calls it repeatedly to determine which books are to be added to the result list and which are to be discarded.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Because the closure has a reference to `threshold`, it can use that variable each time `filter` calls it.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The function `filter` might be defined in a separate file.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The arrow operator `=>` is used to define an arrow function expression, and an `Array.prototype.filter` method instead of a global `filter` function, but otherwise the structure and the effect of the code are the same.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Because the closure in this case outlives the execution of the function that creates it, the variables `f` and `dx` live on after the function `derivative` returns, even though execution has left their scope and they are no longer visible.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In languages without closures, the lifetime of an automatic local variable coincides with the execution of the stack frame where that variable is declared.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In languages with closures, variables must continue to exist as long as any existing closures have references to them.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This is most commonly implemented using some form of garbage collection.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] A closure can be used to associate a function with a set of "private" variables, which persist over several invocations of the function.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The scope of the variable encompasses only the closed-over function, so it cannot be accessed from other program code.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] These are analogous to private variables in object-oriented programming, and in fact closures are similar to stateful function objects (or functors) with a single call-operator method.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In stateful languages, closures can thus be used to implement paradigms for state representation and information hiding, since the closure's upvalues (its closed-over variables) are of indefinite extent, so a value established in one invocation remains available in the next.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Closures used in this way no longer have referential transparency, and are thus no longer pure functions; nevertheless, they are commonly used in impure functional languages such as Scheme.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Note: Some speakers call any data structure that binds a lexical environment a closure, but the term usually refers specifically to functions.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Closures are typically implemented with a special data structure that contains a pointer to the function code, plus a representation of the function's lexical environment (i.e., the set of available variables) at the time when the closure was created.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The referencing environment binds the non-local names to the corresponding variables in the lexical environment at the time the closure is created, additionally extending their lifetime to at least as long as the lifetime of the closure.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] When the closure is entered at a later time, possibly with a different lexical environment, the function is executed with its non-local variables referring to the ones captured by the closure, not the current environment.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] A language implementation cannot easily support full closures if its run-time memory model allocates all automatic variables on a linear stack.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In such languages, a function's automatic local variables are deallocated when the function returns.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] However, a closure requires that the free variables it references survive the enclosing function's execution.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Therefore, those variables must be allocated so that they persist until no longer needed, typically via heap allocation, rather than on the stack, and their lifetime must be managed so they survive until all closures referencing them are no longer in use.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This explains why, typically, languages that natively support closures also use garbage collection.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The funarg problem (or "functional argument" problem) describes the difficulty of implementing functions as first class objects in a stack-based programming language such as C or C++.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] D version 2 solved this by detecting which variables must be stored on the heap, and performs automatic allocation.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Because D uses garbage collection, in both versions, there is no need to track usage of variables as they are passed.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In strict functional languages with immutable data (*e.g.* Erlang), it is very easy to implement automatic memory management (garbage collection), as there are no possible cycles in variables' references.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] For example, in Erlang, all arguments and variables are allocated on the heap, but references to them are additionally stored on the stack.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] After a function returns, references are still valid.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Heap cleaning is done by incremental garbage collector.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In ML, local variables are lexically scoped, and hence define a stack-like model, but since they are bound to values and not to objects, an implementation is free to copy these values into the closure's data structure in a way that is invisible to the programmer.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Scheme, which has an ALGOL-like lexical scope system with dynamic variables and garbage collection, lacks a stack programming model and does not suffer from the limitations of stack-based languages.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Closures are expressed naturally in Scheme.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The lambda form encloses the code, and the free variables of its environment persist within the program as long as they can possibly be accessed, and so they can be used as freely as any other Scheme expression.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Closures are closely related to Actors in the Actor model of concurrent computation where the values in the function's lexical environment are called *acquaintances*.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] An important issue for closures in concurrent programming languages is whether the variables in a closure can be updated and, if so, how these updates can be synchronized.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Closures are closely related to function objects; the transformation from the former to the latter is known as defunctionalization or lambda lifting; see also closure conversion.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] As different languages do not always have a common definition of the lexical environment, their definitions of closure may vary also.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The commonly held minimalist definition of the lexical environment defines it as a set of all bindings of variables in the scope, and that is also what closures in any language have to capture.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] However the meaning of a variable binding also differs.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In imperative languages, variables bind to relative locations in memory that can store values.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Although the relative location of a binding does not change at runtime, the value in the bound location can.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In such languages, since closure captures the binding, any operation on the variable, whether done from the closure or not, are performed on the same relative memory location.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This is often called capturing the variable "by reference".
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Function `foo` and the closures referred to by variables `f` and `g` all use the same relative memory location signified by local variable `x`.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In some instances the above behaviour may be undesirable, and it is necessary to bind a different lexical closure.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Again in ECMAScript, this would be done using the `Function.bind()`.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Again here variable `e` would need to be bound by the scope of the block using `handle.bind(this)` or the `let` keyword.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] On the other hand, many functional languages, such as ML, bind variables directly to values.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In this case, since there is no way to change the value of the variable once it is bound, there is no need to share the state between closures—they just use the same values.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This is often called capturing the variable "by value".
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Java's local and anonymous classes also fall into this category—they require captured local variables to be `final`, which also means there is no need to share state.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Some languages enable choosing between capturing the value of a variable or its location.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] For example, in C++11, captured variables are either declared with `[&]`, which means captured by reference, or with `[=]`, which means captured by value.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Yet another subset, lazy functional languages such as Haskell, bind variables to results of future computations rather than values.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The binding of `r` captured by the closure defined within function `foo` is to the computation `(x / y)`—which in this case results in division by zero.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] However, since it is the computation that is captured, and not the value, the error only manifests when the closure is invoked, and then attempts to use the captured binding.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Yet more differences manifest themselves in the behavior of other lexically scoped constructs, such as `return`, `break` and `continue` statements.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Such constructs can, in general, be considered in terms of invoking an escape continuation established by an enclosing control statement (in case of `break` and `continue`, such interpretation requires looping constructs to be considered in terms of recursive function calls).
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In some languages, such as ECMAScript, `return` refers to the continuation established by the closure lexically innermost with respect to the statement—thus, a `return` within a closure transfers control to the code that called it.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] However, in Smalltalk, the superficially similar operator `^` invokes the escape continuation established for the method invocation, ignoring the escape continuations of any intervening nested closures.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The escape continuation of a particular closure can only be invoked in Smalltalk implicitly by reaching the end of the closure's code.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The above code snippets will behave differently because the Smalltalk `^` operator and the JavaScript `return` operator are not analogous.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In the ECMAScript example, `return x;` will leave the inner closure to begin a new iteration of the `forEach` loop, whereas in the Smalltalk example, `^x` will abort the loop and return from the method `foo`.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Common Lisp provides a construct that can express either of the above actions: Lisp `(return-from foo x)` behaves as Smalltalk `^x`, while Lisp `(return-from nil x)` behaves as JavaScript `return x`.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Hence, Smalltalk makes it possible for a captured escape continuation to outlive the extent in which it can be successfully invoked.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] When the closure returned by the method `foo` is invoked, it attempts to return a value from the invocation of `foo` that created the closure.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Since that call has already returned and the Smalltalk method invocation model does not follow the spaghetti stack discipline to facilitate multiple returns, this operation results in an error.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Some languages, such as Ruby, enable the programmer to choose the way `return` is captured.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Both `Proc.new` and `lambda` in this example are ways to create a closure, but semantics of the closures thus created are different with respect to the `return` statement.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In Scheme, definition and scope of the `return` control statement is explicit (and only arbitrarily named 'return' for the sake of the example).
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The following is a direct translation of the Ruby sample.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Some languages have features which simulate the behavior of closures.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In languages such as C++, C#, D, Java, Objective-C, and Visual Basic (.NET) (VB.NET), these features are the result of the language's object-oriented paradigm.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This is sometimes implemented by providing two values when registering the callback with the library: a function pointer and a separate `void*` pointer to arbitrary data of the user's choice.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] When the library executes the callback function, it passes along the data pointer.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This enables the callback to maintain state and to refer to information captured at the time it was registered with the library.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The idiom is similar to closures in functionality, but not in syntax.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The `void*` pointer is not type safe so this C idiom differs from type-safe closures in C#, Haskell or ML.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] With a GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) extension, a nested function can be used and a function pointer can emulate closures, provided the function does not exit the containing scope.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] If executed this now prints `11` as expected.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Java enables classes to be defined inside methods.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] When such classes are not named, they are known as *anonymous classes* (or anonymous *inner* classes).
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] A local class (either named or anonymous) may refer to names in lexically enclosing classes, or read-only variables (marked as `final`) in the lexically enclosing method.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The capturing of `final` variables enables capturing variables by value.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Even if the variable to capture is non-`final`, it can always be copied to a temporary `final` variable just before the class.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Capturing of variables by reference can be emulated by using a `final` reference to a mutable container, for example, a one-element array.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The local class will not be able to change the value of the container reference, but it will be able to change the contents of the container.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Local classes are one of the types of inner class that are declared within the body of a method.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Java also supports inner classes that are declared as *non-static members* of an enclosing class.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] They are normally referred to just as "inner classes".
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] These are defined in the body of the enclosing class and have full access to instance variables of the enclosing class.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Due to their binding to these instance variables, an inner class may only be instantiated with an explicit binding to an instance of the enclosing class using a special syntax.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Upon execution, this will print the integers from 0 to 9.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Beware to not confuse this type of class with the nested class, which is declared in the same way with an accompanied usage of the "static" modifier; those have not the desired effect but are instead just classes with no special binding defined in an enclosing class.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] As of Java 8, Java supports functions as first class objects.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Lambda expressions of this form are considered of type `java.util.function.Function<T, U>` with T being the domain and U the image type.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The expression can be called with its `Function.apply(T t)` method, but not with a standard method call.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Apple introduced blocks, a form of closure, as a nonstandard extension into C, C++, Objective-C 2.0 and in Mac OS X 10.6 "Snow Leopard" and iOS 4.0.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Apple made their implementation available for the GCC and clang compilers.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Pointers to block and block literals are marked with `^`.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Normal local variables are captured by value when the block is created, and are read-only inside the block.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Variables to be captured by reference are marked with `__block`.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Blocks that need to persist outside of the scope they are created in may need to be copied.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In D, closures are implemented by delegates, a function pointer paired with a context pointer (e.g. a class instance, or a stack frame on the heap in the case of closures).
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] D version 1, has limited closure support.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] For example, the above code will not work correctly, because the variable a is on the stack, and after returning from test(), it is no longer valid to use it (most probably calling foo via dg(), will return a 'random' integer).
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This can be solved by explicitly allocating the variable 'a' on heap, or using structs or class to store all needed closed variables and construct a delegate from a method implementing the same code.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This limitation was fixed in D version 2 - the variable 'a' will be automatically allocated on the heap because it is used in the inner function, and a delegate of that function can escape the current scope (via assignment to dg or return).
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Any other local variables (or arguments) that are not referenced by delegates or that are only referenced by delegates that do not escape the current scope, remain on the stack, which is simpler and faster than heap allocation.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The same is true for inner's class methods that reference a function's variables.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] C++ enables defining function objects by overloading `operator()`.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] These objects behave somewhat like functions in a functional programming language.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] They may be created at runtime and may contain state, but they do not implicitly capture local variables as closures do.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] As of the 2011 revision, the C++ language also supports closures, which are a type of function object constructed automatically from a special language construct called *lambda-expression*.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] A C++ closure may capture its context either by storing copies of the accessed variables as members of the closure object or by reference.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] In the latter case, if the closure object escapes the scope of a referenced object, invoking its `operator()` causes undefined behavior since C++ closures do not extend the lifetime of their context.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] C++ also has the object `std::function<R(Args...)>` for holding an anonymous function.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] However, because anonymous functions have compiler-generated names and are distinct, storing one as a `std::function` uses type erasure which causes minor overhead.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Eiffel includes inline agents defining closures.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] An inline agent is an object representing a routine, defined by giving the code of the routine in-line.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] the argument to `subscribe` is an agent, representing a procedure with two arguments; the procedure finds the country at the corresponding coordinates and displays it.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The whole agent is "subscribed" to the event type `click_event` for a certain button, so that whenever an instance of the event type occurs on that button – because a user has clicked the button – the procedure will be executed with the mouse coordinates being passed as arguments for `x` and `y`.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The main limitation of Eiffel agents, which distinguishes them from closures in other languages, is that they cannot reference local variables from the enclosing scope.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] This design decision helps in avoiding ambiguity when talking about a local variable value in a closure - should it be the latest value of the variable or the value captured when the agent is created?
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Only `Current` (a reference to current object, analogous to `this` in Java), its features, and arguments of the agent can be accessed from within the agent body.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] The values of the outer local variables can be passed by providing additional closed operands to the agent.
[src:closure-conversion/closure-computer-programming] Embarcadero C++Builder provides the reserved word `__closure` to provide a pointer to a method with a similar syntax to a function pointer.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In mathematics, and in other disciplines involving formal languages, including mathematical logic and computer science, a variable may be said to be either free or bound.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Some older books use the terms **real variable** and **apparent variable** for **free variable** and **bound variable**, respectively.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] A *free variable* is a notation (symbol) that specifies places in an expression where substitution may take place and is not a parameter of this or any container expression.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The idea is related to a *placeholder* (a symbol that will later be replaced by some value), or a wildcard character that stands for an unspecified symbol.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In computer programming, the term free variable refers to variables used in a function that are neither local variables nor parameters of that function.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The term non-local variable is often a synonym in this context.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] An instance of a variable symbol is *bound*, in contrast, if the value of that variable symbol has been bound to a specific value or range of values in the domain of discourse or universe.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] A variable symbol overall is **free** if at least one occurrence of it is free.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] While the domain of discourse in many contexts is understood, when an explicit range of values for the bound variable has not been given, it may be necessary to specify the domain in order to properly evaluate the expression.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This expression evaluates to *false* if the domain of x and y is the real numbers, but *true* if the domain is the complex numbers.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In a broader context, bound variables are fundamental to the structure of mathematical proofs.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In this proof, both n and k function as bound variables, but they are bound in different ways.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The variable n is introduced as an *arbitrary but particular* element of a set.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The statement "Let n be..." implicitly functions as a universal quantifier, binding n for the scope of the proof.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The proof establishes a property for this single, arbitrary n , which licenses the general conclusion that the property holds for all positive even integers.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The variable k , on the other hand, is bound by an existential quantifier ("there exists an integer k ").
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] It is introduced to represent a specific, though unnamed, integer whose existence is guaranteed by the definition of n being even.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The scope of k is limited to the reasoning that follows its introduction.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Thus, neither variable is free; their meaning is entirely determined by their role within the logical structure of the proof.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In mathematics and logic, a number of symbols function as **variable-binding operators**.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] These operators take a function or an open formula as an argument and bind a free variable within that expression to a specific domain or range of values, creating a new expression whose meaning does not depend on the bound variable.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In each case, the variable *x* is bound within the expression that follows the operator (e.g., $f(x)$ or $P(x)$ ).
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Many of these operators act on a function of the bound variable.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] While standard notation is often sufficient, complex expressions with nested operators can become ambiguous, particularly if the same variable name is reused.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This can lead to a problem known as *variable capture*, where a variable intended to be free is incorrectly bound by an operator in a different scope.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] To avoid such ambiguity, it can be useful to switch to a notation that makes the binding explicit, treating the operators as higher-order functions.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This approach, rooted in the principles of lambda calculus, clearly separates the function being operated on from the operator itself.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Here, the operator $\sum _{S}f$ applies to the set *S* and the function *f*.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This notation clarifies that the operator D is applied to the entire function $x\mapsto x^{2}+2x+1$ , rather than just an expression in which x happens to be a variable.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Variable-binding mechanisms occur in different contexts in mathematics, logic and computer science.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In all cases, however, they are purely syntactic properties of expressions and variables in them.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] For this section we can summarize syntax by identifying an expression with a tree whose leaf nodes are variables, constants, function constants or predicate constants and whose non-leaf nodes are logical operators.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This expression can then be determined by doing an in-order traversal of the tree.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Variable-binding operators are logical operators that occur in almost every formal language.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] A binding operator Q takes two arguments: a variable v and an expression P , and when applied to its arguments produces a new expression $Q(v,P)$ .
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The meaning of binding operators is supplied by the semantics of the language and does not concern us here.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Variable binding relates three things: a variable v , a location a for that variable in an expression and a non-leaf node n of the form $Q(v,P)$ .
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] It worth noting that we define a location in an expression as a leaf node in the syntax tree.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Variable binding occurs when that location is below the node n .
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In the lambda calculus, `x` is a bound variable in the term `M = λx.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] We say `x` is bound in `M` and free in `T`.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This nested, inner binding of `x` is said to "shadow" the outer binding.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Occurrences of `x` in `U` are free occurrences of the new `x`.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Variables bound at the top level of a program are technically free variables within the terms to which they are bound but are often treated specially because they can be compiled as fixed addresses.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Similarly, an identifier bound to a recursive function is also technically a free variable within its own body but is treated specially.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] A *closed term* is one containing no free variables.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] A clear example of a variable-binding operator from mathematics is function definition.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The expression t , which forms the body of the function, may contain some, all, or none of the variables $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ , which are its formal parameters.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Any occurrence of these variables within t is bound by the function definition.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The body t may also contain other variables, which would be considered free variables whose values must be determined from a wider context.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The expression $\left[(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})\mapsto t\right]$ is directly analogous to lambda expressions in lambda calculus, where the $\lambda$ symbol is the fundamental variable-binding operator.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] For instance, the function definition $(x\mapsto x^{2})$ is equivalent to the lambda abstraction $\lambda x.x^{2}$ .
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Other mathematical operators can be understood as higher-order functions that bind variables.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] For example, the summation operator, $\Sigma$ , can be analyzed as an operator that takes a function and a set to evaluate that function over.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] binds the variable *x* within the term $x^{2}$ .
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The scope of the binding is the term that follows the summation symbol.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Here, $\sum _{S}{f}$ is an operator with two parameters: a one-parameter function f (in this case, $x\mapsto x^{2}$ ) and a set S to evaluate that function over.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Other operators can be expressed in a similar manner.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The universal quantifier $\forall x\in S,P(x)$ can be understood as an operator that evaluates to the logical conjunction of the Boolean-valued function P applied to each element in the (possibly infinite) set S .
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Likewise, the product operator ( ${\textstyle \prod }$ ), the limit operator ( $\lim _{n\to \infty }$ ), and the integral operator ( $\int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx$ ) all function as variable binders, binding the variables n and x respectively over a specified domain.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] When analyzed through the lens of formal semantics, natural languages exhibit a system of variable binding that is analogous to what is found in formal logic and computer science.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This system governs how referring expressions, particularly pronouns, are interpreted within a sentence or discourse.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In English, personal pronouns such as *he*, *she*, *they*, and their variants (e.g., *her*, *him*) can function as **free variables**.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] A free variable is a term whose referent is not determined within the immediate syntactic structure of the sentence and must be identified by the broader context, which can be either linguistic or situational (pragmatic).
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The possessive pronoun *her* is a free variable.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Its interpretation is flexible; it can refer to *Lisa*, an entity within the sentence, or to some other female individual salient in the context of the utterance.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This ambiguity leads to two primary interpretations, which can be formally represented using co-indexing subscripts.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] An identical subscript indicates coreference, while different subscripts signal that the expressions refer to different entities.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This distinction is not merely a theoretical exercise.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Some languages have distinct pronominal forms to differentiate between these two readings.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] For example, Norwegian and Swedish use the reflexive possessive *sin* for the coreferential reading (*her*i) and a non-reflexive form like *hennes* (in Swedish) for the non-coreferential reading (*her*j).
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] While English does not have this explicit distinction in its standard pronouns, it can force a coreferential reading by using the emphatic possessive *own*.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In contrast to personal pronouns, reflexive pronouns (e.g., *himself*, *herself*, *themselves*) and reciprocal pronouns (e.g., *each other*) act as **bound variables**, also known in linguistics as **anaphors**.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] A bound variable is an expression that must be co-indexed with, and c-commanded by, an antecedent within a specific syntactic domain.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The reflexive pronoun *herself* must refer to the subject of the clause, *Jane*.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] It cannot refer to any other individual.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This obligatory coreference is a hallmark of a bound variable.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This binding relationship can be formally captured using a lambda expression, a tool from lambda calculus used in formal semantics to model function abstraction and application.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The expression evaluates to "Jane hurt Jane," correctly capturing the fact that the subject and object of the verb are the same entity.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The distinct behavior of pronouns and anaphors is systematically explained by the **binding theory**, a central component of Noam Chomsky's Government and Binding Theory.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The concept of variable binding is essential for understanding quantificational noun phrases (QNPs), such as *every student*, *some politician*, or *no one*.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Unlike proper names, these phrases do not refer to a specific entity.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Instead, they express a quantity over a set of individuals.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] A QNP can bind a pronoun that falls within its scope, making the pronoun a bound variable.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In this sentence, the pronoun *he* is most naturally interpreted as a bound variable.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Its reference co-varies with the individuals in the set denoted by "every student".
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The sentence does not mean that every student thinks a specific person (e.g., Peter) is smart; rather, it means that for each individual student x , x thinks that x is smart.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In syntactic theories, this is often analyzed via a process of quantifier raising (QR), where the QNP moves at the abstract syntactic level of logical form to a position where it c-commands and binds the pronoun.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Variable binding is also central to the analysis of wh-movement, which occurs in the formation of questions and relative clauses.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] *Wh*-words like *who*, *what*, and *which* function as operators that bind a variable in the main clause.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] In these structures, the *wh*-word is said to move from an underlying position, leaving behind a "trace" $(t)$ , which is treated as a bound variable.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The meaning of the question can be paraphrased as "For which person x , does John like x ?".
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Similarly, the relative clause denotes a set of individuals x such that "Mary saw x ".
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The distinction between free and bound variables provides a powerful explanation for certain ambiguities that arise under VP-ellipsis.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] **Sloppy identity:** Bill loves *Bill's* mother.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] This ambiguity can be explained by the status of the pronoun *his* in the first clause.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The existence of the sloppy identity reading is considered strong evidence for the psychological reality of bound variable interpretations in the grammar of natural languages.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] Thus, the distribution and interpretation of pronouns and other referring expressions in natural languages are not random but are governed by a sophisticated syntactic and semantic system.
[src:closure-conversion/free-variables-and-bound-variables] The distinction between free and bound variables is a cornerstone of modern linguistic theory, providing the analytical tools necessary to account for coreference, quantification, question formation, and ellipsis.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In computer programming, the **scope** of a name binding (an association of a name to an entity, such as a variable) is the part of a program in which the name binding is valid.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In other words, a scope is where a name can be used to refer to an entity.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In other parts of the program, the name may refer to a different entity (it may have a different binding), or to nothing at all (it may be unbound).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Scope helps prevent name collisions by allowing the same name to refer to different objects – as long as the names have separate scopes.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The scope of a name binding is also known as the **visibility** of an entity, particularly in older or more technical literature—this is in relation to the referenced entity, not the referencing name.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The term "scope" is also used to refer to the set of *all* name bindings that are valid within a part of a program or at a given point in a program, which is more correctly referred to as *context* or *environment*.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Strictly speaking and in practice for most programming languages, "part of a program" refers to a portion of source code (area of text), and is known as **lexical scope**.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In some languages, however, "part of a program" refers to a portion of run time (period during execution), and is known as **dynamic scope**.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Both of these terms are somewhat misleading—they misuse technical terms, as discussed in the definition—but the distinction itself is accurate and precise, and these are the standard respective terms.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Lexical scope is the main focus of this article, with dynamic scope understood by contrast with lexical scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Difficulties arise in name masking, forward declarations, and hoisting, while considerably subtler ones arise with non-local variables, particularly in closures.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The strict definition of the (lexical) "scope" of a name (identifier) is unambiguous: lexical scope is "the portion of source code in which a binding of a name with an entity applies".
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This is virtually unchanged from its 1960 definition in the specification of ALGOL 60.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The following kinds of quantities are distinguished: simple variables, arrays, labels, switches, and procedures.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The scope of a quantity is the set of statements and expressions in which the declaration of the identifier associated with that quantity is valid.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] name; a label name; a macro name; or a macro parameter.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] A declaration binds a non-blank identifier to a constant, type, variable, function, label, or package. [...] The scope of a declared identifier is the extent of source text in which the identifier denotes the specified constant, type, variable, function, label, or package.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Most commonly "scope" refers to when a given name can refer to a given variable—when a declaration has effect—but can also apply to other entities, such as functions, types, classes, labels, constants, and enumerations.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] A fundamental distinction in scope is what "part of a program" means.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In languages with **lexical scope** (also called **static scope**), name resolution depends on the location in the source code and the *lexical context* (also called *static context*), which is defined by where the named variable or function is defined.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In contrast, in languages with **dynamic scope,** the name resolution depends upon the program state when the name is encountered which is determined by the *execution context* (also called *runtime context*, *calling context* or *dynamic context*).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Most modern languages use lexical scope for variables and functions, though dynamic scope is used in some languages, notably some dialects of Lisp, some "scripting" languages, and some template languages.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Perl 5 offers both lexical and dynamic scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Functions that use lexically scoped variables are known as closures.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Lexical resolution can be determined at compile time, and is also known as *early binding*, while dynamic resolution can in general only be determined at run time, and thus is known as *late binding*.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In object-oriented programming, dynamic dispatch selects an object method at runtime, though whether the actual name binding is done at compile time or run time depends on the language.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] De facto dynamic scope is common in macro languages, which do not directly do name resolution, but instead expand in place.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Some programming frameworks like AngularJS use syntactically the term "scope" to mean — the semantics of word — something entirely different than how it is used in this article.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In those frameworks, the scope is just an object of the programming language that they use (JavaScript in case of AngularJS) that is used in certain ways by the framework to emulate dynamic scope in a language that uses lexical scope for its variables.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Those AngularJS scopes can themselves be in context or not in context (using the usual meaning of the term) in any given part of the program, following the usual rules of variable scope of the language like any other object, and using their own inheritance and transclusion rules.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In the context of AngularJS, sometimes the term "$scope" (with a dollar sign) is used to avoid confusion, but using the dollar sign in variable names is often discouraged by the style guides.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Scope is an important component of name resolution, which is in turn fundamental to language semantics.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Name resolution (including scope) varies between programming languages, and within a programming language, varies by type of entity; the rules for scope are called **scope rules** (or **scoping rules**).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Together with namespaces, scope rules are crucial in modular programming, so a change in one part of the program does not break an unrelated part.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Execution context consists of lexical context (at the current execution point) plus additional runtime state such as the call stack.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Strictly speaking, during execution a program enters and exits various name bindings' scopes, and at a point in execution name bindings are "in context" or "not in context", hence name bindings "come into context" or "go out of context" as the program execution enters or exits the scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] However, in practice usage is much looser.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Scope is a source-code level concept, and a property of name bindings, particularly variable or function name bindings—names in the source code are references to entities in the program—and is part of the behavior of a compiler or interpreter of a language.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] As such, issues of scope are similar to pointers, which are a type of reference used in programs more generally.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Using the value of a variable when the name is in context but the variable is uninitialized is analogous to dereferencing (accessing the value of) a wild pointer, as it is undefined.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] However, as variables are not destroyed until they go out of context, the analog of a dangling pointer does not exist.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Determining which entity a name refers to is known as name resolution or name binding (particularly in object-oriented programming), and varies between languages.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Given a name, the language (properly, the compiler or interpreter) checks all entities that are in context for matches; in case of ambiguity (two entities with the same name, such as a global and local variable with the same name), the name resolution rules are used to distinguish them.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Most frequently, name resolution relies on an "inner-to-outer context" rule, such as the Python LEGB (Local, Enclosing, Global, Built-in) rule: names implicitly resolve to the narrowest relevant context.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In some cases name resolution can be explicitly specified, such as by the `global` and `nonlocal` keywords in Python; in other cases the default rules cannot be overridden.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] When two identical names are in context at the same time, referring to different entities, one says that *name masking* is occurring, where the higher-priority name (usually innermost) is "masking" the lower-priority name.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] At the level of variables, this is known as variable shadowing.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Due to the potential for logic errors from masking, some languages disallow or discourage masking, raising an error or warning at compile time or run time.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Various programming languages have various different scope rules for different kinds of declarations and names.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Such scope rules have a large effect on language semantics and, consequently, on the behavior and correctness of programs.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In languages like C++, accessing an unbound variable does not have well-defined semantics and may result in undefined behavior, similar to referring to a dangling pointer; and declarations or names used outside their scope will generate syntax errors.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Scopes are frequently tied to other language constructs and determined implicitly, but many languages also offer constructs specifically for controlling scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Scope can vary from as little as a single expression to as much as the entire program, with many possible gradations in between.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The simplest scope rule is global scope—all entities are visible throughout the entire program.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The most basic modular scope rule is two-level scope, with a global scope anywhere in the program, and local scope within a function.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] More sophisticated modular programming allows a separate module scope, where names are visible within the module (private to the module) but not visible outside it.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Within a function, some languages, such as C, allow block scope to restrict scope to a subset of a function; others, notably functional programming languages, allow expression scope, to restrict scope to a single expression.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Other scopes include file scope (notably in C) which behaves similarly to module scope, and block scope outside of functions (notably in Perl).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] A subtle issue is exactly when a scope begins and ends.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In some languages, such as C, a name's scope begins at the name declaration, and thus different names declared within a given block can have different scopes.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This requires declaring functions before use, though not necessarily defining them, and requires forward declaration in some cases, notably for mutual recursion.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In other languages, such as Python, a name's scope begins at the start of the relevant block where the name is declared (such as the start of a function), regardless of where it is defined, so all names within a given block have the same scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In JavaScript, the scope of a name declared with `let` or `const` begins at the name declaration, and the scope of a name declared with `var` begins at the start of the function where the name is declared, which is known as *variable hoisting*.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Behavior of names in context that have undefined value differs: in Python use of undefined names yields a runtime error, while in JavaScript undefined names declared with `var` are usable throughout the function because they are implicitly bound to the value `undefined`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The scope of a name binding is an expression, which is known as **expression scope**.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Expression scope is available in many languages, especially functional languages which offer a feature called *let expressions* allowing a declaration's scope to be a single expression.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This is convenient if, for example, an intermediate value is needed for a computation.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] For example, in Standard ML, if `f()` returns `12`, then `**let val** x = f() **in** x * x **end**` is an expression that evaluates to `144`, using a temporary variable named `x` to avoid calling `f()` twice.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Some languages with block scope approximate this functionality by offering syntax for a block to be embedded into an expression; for example, the aforementioned Standard ML expression could be written in Perl as `do { my $x = f(); $x * $x }`, or in GNU C as `({ int x = f(); x * x; })`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In Python, auxiliary variables in generator expressions and list comprehensions (in Python 3) have expression scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In C, variable names in a function prototype have expression scope, known in this context as **function protocol scope**.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] As the variable names in the prototype are not referred to (they may be different in the actual definition)—they are just dummies—these are often omitted, though they may be used for generating documentation, for instance.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The scope of a name binding is a block, which is known as **block scope**.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Block scope is available in many, but not all, block-structured programming languages.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This began with ALGOL 60, where "[e]very declaration ... is valid only for that block.", and today is particularly associated with languages in the Pascal and C families and traditions.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Most often this block is contained within a function, thus restricting the scope to a part of a function, but in some cases, such as Perl, the block may not be within a function.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] A representative example of the use of block scope is the C code shown here, where two variables are scoped to the loop: the loop variable *n*, which is initialized once and incremented on each iteration of the loop, and the auxiliary variable *n_squared*, which is initialized at each iteration.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The purpose is to avoid adding variables to the function scope that are only relevant to a particular block—for example, this prevents errors where the generic loop variable *i* has accidentally already been set to another value.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In this example the expression `n * n` would generally not be assigned to an auxiliary variable, and the body of the loop would simply be written `result += n * n` but in more complicated examples auxiliary variables are useful.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Blocks are primarily used for control flow, such as with if, while, and for loops, and in these cases block scope means the scope of variable depends on the structure of a function's flow of execution.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] However, languages with block scope typically also allow the use of "naked" blocks, whose sole purpose is to allow fine-grained control of variable scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] For example, an auxiliary variable may be defined in a block, then used (say, added to a variable with function scope) and discarded when the block ends, or a while loop might be enclosed in a block that initializes variables used inside the loop that should only be initialized once.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] A subtlety of several programming languages, such as Algol 68 and C (demonstrated in this example and standardized since C99), is that block-scope variables can be declared not only within the body of the block, but also within the control statement, if any.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This is analogous to function parameters, which are declared in the function declaration (before the block of the function body starts), and in scope for the whole function body.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This is primarily used in for loops, which have an initialization statement separate from the loop condition, unlike while loops, and is a common idiom.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In this example, inside the block the auxiliary variable could also have been called *n*, shadowing the parameter name, but this is considered poor style due to the potential for errors.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Furthermore, some descendants of C, such as Java and C#, despite having support for block scope (in that a local variable can be made to go out of context before the end of a function), do not allow one local variable to hide another.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In such languages, the attempted declaration of the second *n* would result in a syntax error, and one of the *n* variables would have to be renamed.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] If a block is used to set the value of a variable, block scope requires that the variable be declared outside of the block.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This complicates the use of conditional statements with single assignment.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] where `a` is accessible after the `if` statement.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Often this is instead rewritten using multiple assignment, initializing the variable to a default value.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In case of a single variable assignment, an alternative is to use the ternary operator to avoid a block, but this is not in general possible for multiple variable assignments, and is difficult to read for complex logic.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This is a more significant issue in C, notably for string assignment, as string initialization can automatically allocate memory, while string assignment to an already initialized variable requires allocating memory, a string copy, and checking that these are successful.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Some languages allow the concept of block scope to be applied, to varying extents, outside of a function.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] For example, in the Perl snippet at right, `$counter` is a variable name with block scope (due to the use of the `my` keyword), while `increment_counter` is a function name with global scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Each call to `increment_counter` will increase the value of `$counter` by one, and return the new value.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Code outside of this block can call `increment_counter`, but cannot otherwise obtain or alter the value of `$counter`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This idiom allows one to define closures in Perl.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] When the scope of variables declared within a function does not extend beyond that function, this is known as **function scope**.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Function scope is available in most programming languages which offer a way to create a *local variable* in a function or subroutine: a variable whose scope ends (that goes out of context) when the function returns.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] However, some languages, such as C, also provide for static local variables, where the lifetime of the variable is the entire lifetime of the program, but the variable is only in context when inside the function.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In the case of static local variables, the variable is created when the program initializes, and destroyed only when the program terminates, as with a static global variable, but is only in context within a function, like an automatic local variable.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In languages with lexical scope and nested functions, local variables are in context for nested functions, since these are within the same lexical context, but not for other functions that are not lexically nested.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] A local variable of an enclosing function is known as a non-local variable for the nested function.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Function scope is also applicable to anonymous functions.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] For example, in the snippet of Python code on the right, two functions are defined: `square` and `sum_of_squares`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] `square` computes the square of a number; `sum_of_squares` computes the sum of all squares up to a number.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Each of these functions has a variable named *n* that represents the argument to the function.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] These two *n* variables are completely separate and unrelated, despite having the same name, because they are lexically scoped local variables with function scope: each one's scope is its own, lexically separate function and thus, they don't overlap.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Therefore, `sum_of_squares` can call `square` without its own *n* being altered.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Similarly, `sum_of_squares` has variables named *total* and *i*; these variables, because of their limited scope, will not interfere with any variables named *total* or *i* that might belong to any other function.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In other words, there is no risk of a *name collision* between these names and any unrelated names, even if they are identical.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] No name masking is occurring: only one variable named *n* is in context at any given time, as the scopes do not overlap.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] By contrast, were a similar fragment to be written in a language with dynamic scope, the *n* in the calling function would remain in context in the called function—the scopes would overlap—and would be masked ("shadowed") by the new *n* in the called function.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Function scope is significantly more complicated if functions are first-class objects and can be created locally by a function and then returned.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This requires significantly more support from the compiler, and can complicate program analysis.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The scope of a name binding is a file, which is known as **file scope**.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] File scope is largely particular to C (and C++), where scope of variables and functions declared at the top level of a file (not within any function) is for the entire file—or rather for C, from the declaration until the end of the source file, or more precisely translation unit (internal linking).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This can be seen as a form of module scope, where modules are identified with files, and in more modern languages is replaced by an explicit module scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Due to the presence of include statements, which add variables and functions to the internal context and may themselves call further include statements, it can be difficult to determine what is in context in the body of a file.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In the C code snippet above, the function name `sum_of_squares` has global scope (in C, extern linkage).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Adding `static` to the function signature would result in file scope (internal linkage).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The scope of a name binding is a module, which is known as **module scope**.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Module scope is available in modular programming languages where modules (which may span various files) are the basic unit of a complex program, as they allow information hiding and exposing a limited interface.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Module scope was pioneered in the Modula family of languages, and Python (which was influenced by Modula) is a representative contemporary example.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In some object-oriented programming languages that lack direct support for modules, such as C++ before C++20, a similar structure is instead provided by the class hierarchy, where classes are the basic unit of the program, and a class can have private methods.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This is properly understood in the context of dynamic dispatch rather than name resolution and scope, though they often play analogous roles.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In some cases both these facilities are available, such as in Python, which has both modules and classes, and code organization (as a module-level function or a conventionally private method) is a choice of the programmer.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The scope of a name binding is an entire program, which is known as **global scope**.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Variable names with global scope—called *global variables*—are frequently considered bad practice, at least in some languages, due to the possibility of name collisions and unintentional masking, together with poor modularity, and function scope or block scope are considered preferable.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] However, global scope is typically used (depending on the language) for various other sorts of names, such as names of functions, names of classes and names of other data types.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In these cases mechanisms such as namespaces are used to avoid collisions.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The use of local variables — of variable names with limited scope, that only exist within a specific function — helps avoid the risk of a name collision between two identically named variables.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] However, there are two very different approaches to answering this question: What does it mean to be "within" a function?
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Consider, for example, the program on the right.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The first line, `x=1`, creates a global variable `x` and initializes it to `1`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The second line, `function g() { echo $x ; x=2 ; }`, defines a function `g` that prints out ("echoes") the current value of `x`, and then sets `x` to `2` (overwriting the prior value).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The third line, `function f() { local x=3 ; g ; }` defines a function `f` that creates a local variable `x` (hiding the identically named global variable) and initializes it to `3`, and then calls `g`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The fifth line, `echo $x`, prints out the current value of `x`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The scope rules determine what this program prints.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] If the language of this program is one that uses lexical scope, then `g` prints and modifies the global variable `x` (because `g` is defined outside `f`), so the program prints `1` and then `2`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] By contrast, if this language uses dynamic scope, then `g` prints and modifies `f`'s local variable `x` (because `g` is called from within `f`), so the program prints `3` and then `1`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] (As it happens, the language of the program is Bash, which uses dynamic scope; so the program prints `3` and then `1`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] With **lexical scope**, a name always refers to its lexical context.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This is a property of the program text and is made independent of the runtime call stack by the language implementation.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Because this matching only requires analysis of the static program text, this type of scope is also called **static scope**.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Lexical scope is standard in all ALGOL-based languages such as Pascal, Modula-2, and Ada, and in modern functional languages such as ML and Haskell.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] It is also used in the C language and its syntactic and semantic relatives, although with different kinds of limitations.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Static scope allows the programmer to reason about object references such as parameters, variables, constants, types, functions, etc., as simple name substitutions.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This makes it much easier to make modular code and reason about it, since the local naming structure can be understood in isolation.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In contrast, dynamic scope forces the programmer to anticipate all possible execution contexts in which the module's code may be invoked.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] For example, Pascal is lexically scoped.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Consider the Pascal program fragment at right.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The variable `I` is visible at all points, because it is never hidden by another variable of the same name.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The `char` variable `K` is visible only in the main program because it is hidden by the `real` variable `K` visible only in procedures `A` and `B`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Variable `L` is also visible only in procedure `A` and `B` but it does not hide any other variable.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Variable `M` is only visible in procedure `B` and therefore not accessible either from procedure `A` or the main program.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Also, procedure `B` is visible only in procedure `A` and can therefore not be called from the main program.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] There could have been another procedure named `B` declared in the program outside of procedure `B`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The place in the program where "`B`" is mentioned then determines which of the two procedures named `B` it represents, analogous with the scope of variables.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Correct implementation of lexical scope in languages with first-class nested functions is not trivial, as it requires each function value to carry with it a record of the values of the variables that it depends on (the pair of the function and this context is called a closure).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Depending on implementation and computer architecture, variable lookup *may* become slightly inefficient when very deeply lexically nested functions are used, although there are well-known techniques to mitigate this.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Also, for nested functions that only refer to their own arguments and (immediately) local variables, all relative locations can be known at compile time.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] No overhead at all is therefore incurred when using that type of nested function.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The same applies to particular parts of a program where nested functions are not used, and, naturally, to programs written in a language where nested functions are not available (such as in the C language).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Lexical scope was first used in the early 1960s for the imperative language ALGOL 60 and has been picked up in most other imperative languages since then.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Languages like Pascal and C have always had lexical scope, since they are both influenced by the ideas that went into ALGOL 60 and ALGOL 68 (although C did not include lexically nested functions).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Perl is a language with dynamic scope that added static scope afterwards.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The original Lisp interpreter (1960) used dynamic scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] *Deep binding*, which approximates static (lexical) scope, was introduced around 1962 in LISP 1.5 (via the Funarg device developed by Steve Russell, working under John McCarthy).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] All early Lisps used dynamic scope, when based on interpreters.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Steele Jr. and the Common Lisp Group published *An overview of Common Lisp*, a short review of the history and the divergent implementations of Lisp up to that moment and a review of the features that a *Common Lisp* implementation should have.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Implementations of Common Lisp were thus required to have lexical scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] By the same year in which *An overview of Common LISP* was published (1982), initial designs (also by Guy L.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Steele Jr.) of a compiled, lexically scoped Lisp, called *Scheme* had been published and compiler implementations were being attempted.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] At that time, lexical scope in Lisp was commonly feared to be inefficient to implement.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The term "lexical scope" dates at least to 1967, while the term "lexical scoping" dates at least to 1970, where it was used in Project MAC to describe the scope rules of the Lisp dialect MDL (then known as "Muddle").
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In modern programming languages, lexical scope plays a crucial role in enabling functional programming paradigms.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Languages like JavaScript, Python, and Swift rely heavily on lexical scoping to ensure that functions can access variables from their defining context, even if the function is executed outside its lexical scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This is particularly important when dealing with closures, which are a direct consequence of lexical scoping.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] For example, in JavaScript, closures are frequently used for asynchronous programming and event handling, as they allow callbacks to retain access to the variables from the outer scope, facilitating cleaner, more modular code.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Similarly, Python and Swift utilize lexical scope to implement closures and enable powerful patterns like higher-order functions.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] With **dynamic scope**, a name refers to execution context.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In technical terms, this means that each name has a global stack of bindings.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Introducing a local variable with name `x` pushes a binding onto the global `x` stack (which may have been empty), which is popped off when the control flow leaves the scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Evaluating `x` in any context always yields the top binding.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Note that this cannot be done at compile-time because the binding stack only exists at run-time, which is why this type of scope is called *dynamic* scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Dynamic scope is uncommon in modern languages.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Generally, certain blocks are defined to create bindings whose lifetime is the execution time of the block; this adds some features of static scope to the dynamic scope process.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] However, since a section of code can be called from many different locations and situations, it can be difficult to determine at the outset what bindings will apply when a variable is used (or if one exists at all).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This can be beneficial; application of the principle of least knowledge suggests that code avoid depending on the *reasons* for (or circumstances of) a variable's value, but simply use the value according to the variable's definition.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This narrow interpretation of shared data can provide a very flexible system for adapting the behavior of a function to the current state (or policy) of the system.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] However, this benefit relies on careful documentation of all variables used this way and on careful avoidance of assumptions about a variable's behavior, and provides no mechanism to detect interference between different parts of a program.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Some languages, like Perl and Common Lisp, allow a programmer to choose static or dynamic scope when defining or redefining a variable.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Examples of languages that use dynamic scope include Logo, Emacs Lisp, LaTeX and the shell languages bash, dash, and PowerShell.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Dynamic scope is fairly easy to implement.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] To find a name's value, the program could traverse the runtime stack, checking each activation record (each function's stack frame) for a value for the name.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In practice, this is made more efficient via the use of an association list, which is a stack of name/value pairs.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Pairs are pushed onto this stack whenever declarations are made, and popped whenever variables go out of context.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] *Shallow binding* is an alternative strategy that is considerably faster, making use of a *central reference table*, which associates each name with its own stack of meanings.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This avoids a linear search during run-time to find a particular name, but care should be taken to properly maintain this table.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Note that both of these strategies assume a last-in-first-out (LIFO) ordering to bindings for any one variable; in practice all bindings are so ordered.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] An even simpler implementation is the representation of dynamic variables with simple global variables.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The local binding is performed by saving the original value in an anonymous location on the stack that is invisible to the program.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] When that binding scope terminates, the original value is restored from this location.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In fact, dynamic scope originated in this manner.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Early implementations of Lisp used this obvious strategy for implementing local variables, and the practice survives in some dialects which are still in use, such as GNU Emacs Lisp.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Lexical scope was introduced into Lisp later.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] This is equivalent to the above shallow binding scheme, except that the central reference table is simply the global variable binding context, in which the current meaning of the variable is its global value.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Maintaining global variables isn't complex.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] For instance, a symbol object can have a dedicated slot for its global value.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Dynamic scope provides an excellent abstraction for thread-local storage, but if it is used that way it cannot be based on saving and restoring a global variable.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] A possible implementation strategy is for each variable to have a thread-local key.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] When the variable is accessed, the thread-local key is used to access the thread-local memory location (by code generated by the compiler, which knows which variables are dynamic and which are lexical).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] If no thread-local key exists for the calling thread, then the global location is used.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] When a variable is locally bound, the prior value is stored in a hidden location on the stack.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The thread-local storage is created under the variable's key, and the new value is stored there.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Further nested overrides of the variable within that thread simply save and restore this thread-local location.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] When the initial, outermost override's context terminates, the thread-local key is deleted, exposing the global version of the variable once again to that thread.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] With referential transparency the dynamic scope is restricted to the argument stack of the current function only, and coincides with the lexical scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] In modern languages, macro expansion in a preprocessor is a key example of de facto dynamic scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The C preprocessor, used for macro expansion, has de facto dynamic scope, as it does not resolve names by itself and it is independent of where the macro is defined.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] will expand to add `a` to the passed variable, with this name only later resolved by the compiler based on where the macro `ADD_A` is "called" (properly, expanded).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Properly, the C preprocessor only does lexical analysis, expanding the macro during the tokenization stage, but not parsing into a syntax tree or doing name resolution.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] As we have seen, one of the key reasons for scope is that it helps prevent name collisions, by allowing identical names to refer to distinct things, with the restriction that the names must have separate scopes.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Sometimes this restriction is inconvenient; when many different things need to be accessible throughout a program, they generally all need names with global scope, so different techniques are required to avoid name collisions.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] To address this, many languages offer mechanisms for organizing global names.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] The details of these mechanisms, and the terms used, depend on the language; but the general idea is that a group of names can itself be given a name — a prefix — and, when necessary, an entity can be referred to by a *qualified name* consisting of the name plus the prefix.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Normally such names will have, in a sense, two sets of scopes: a scope (usually the global scope) in which the qualified name is visible, and one or more narrower scopes in which the *unqualified name* (without the prefix) is visible as well.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] And normally these groups can themselves be organized into groups; that is, they can be *nested*.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Although many languages support this concept, the details vary greatly.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Some languages have mechanisms, such as *namespaces* in C++ and C#, that serve almost exclusively to enable global names to be organized into groups.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] Other languages have mechanisms, such as *packages* in Ada and *structures* in Standard ML, that combine this with the additional purpose of allowing some names to be visible only to other members of their group.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p01] And object-oriented languages often allow classes or singleton objects to fulfill this purpose (whether or not they *also* have a mechanism for which this is the primary purpose).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Scope rules for representative languages follow.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] In C, scope is traditionally known as **linkage** or **visibility**, particularly for variables.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] C is a lexically scoped language with global scope (known as *external linkage*), a form of module scope or file scope (known as *internal linkage*), and local scope (within a function); within a function scopes can further be nested via block scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] However, standard C does not support nested functions.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] The lifetime and visibility of a variable are determined by its storage class.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] There are three types of lifetimes in C: static (program execution), automatic (block execution, allocated on the stack), and manual (allocated on the heap).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Only static and automatic are supported for variables and handled by the compiler, while manually allocated memory must be tracked manually across different variables.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] There are three levels of visibility in C: external linkage (global), internal linkage (roughly file), and block scope (which includes functions); block scopes can be nested, and different levels of internal linkage is possible by use of includes.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Internal linkage in C is visibility at the translation unit level, namely a source file after being processed by the C preprocessor, notably including all relevant includes.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] C programs are compiled as separate object files, which are then linked into an executable or library via a linker.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Thus name resolution is split across the compiler, which resolves names within a translation unit (more loosely, "compilation unit", but this is properly a different concept), and the linker, which resolves names across translation units; see linkage for further discussion.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] In C, variables with block scope enter context when they are declared (not at the top of the block), go out of context if any (non-nested) function is called within the block, come back into context when the function returns, and go out of context at the end of the block.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] In the case of automatic local variables, they are also allocated on declaration and deallocated at the end of the block, while for static local variables, they are allocated at program initialization and deallocated at program termination.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Variable names used in a function prototype have function prototype visibility, and exit context at the end of the function prototype.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Since the name is not used, this is not useful for compilation, but may be useful for documentation.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Label names for GOTO statement have function scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] All the variables to use in a program must have been declared with its type specifier in an earlier point in the code, as done in the prior code at the start of the body of the function `main` when declaring that a, b, and result were of type int.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] A variable can be either of global or local scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] A global variable is a variable declared in the main body of the source code, outside all functions, while a local variable is one declared within the body of a function or a block.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Modern versions allow nested lexical scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Swift has a similar rule for scopes with C++, but contains different access modifiers.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] are defined inside a method, or a particular block.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] These variables are local to where they were defined and lower levels.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] For example, a loop inside a method can use that method's local variables, but not the other way around.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] The loop's variables (local to that loop) are destroyed as soon as the loop ends.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] are variables declared within the class, outside of any method.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] By default, these variables are available for all methods within that class and also for all classes in the package.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] In general, a set of brackets defines a particular scope, but variables at top level within a class can differ in their behavior depending on the modifier keywords used in their definition.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] The following table shows the access to members permitted by each modifier.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] JavaScript objects have name resolution for properties, but this is a separate topic.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] JavaScript has lexical scope nested at the function level, with the global context being the outermost context.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] This scope is used for both variables and for functions (meaning function declarations, as opposed to variables of function type).
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Block scope with the `let` and `const` keywords is standard since ECMAScript 6.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Block scope can be produced by wrapping the entire block in a function and then executing it; this is known as the immediately-invoked function expression (IIFE) pattern.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] While JavaScript scope is simple—lexical, function-level—the associated initialization and name resolution rules are a cause of confusion.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Firstly, assignment to a name not in scope defaults to creating a new global variable, not a local one.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] is executed, not when the variable is created.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] This is known as *variable hoisting*—the declaration, but not the initialization, is hoisted to the top of the function.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Thirdly, accessing variables before initialization yields `undefined`, rather than a syntax error.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Fourthly, for function declarations, the declaration and the initialization are both hoisted to the top of the function, unlike for variable initialization.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] The nested scopes of a particular function (from most global to most local) in JavaScript, particularly of a closure, used as a callback, are sometimes referred to as the **scope chain**, by analogy with the prototype chain of an object.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Closures can be produced in JavaScript by using nested functions, as functions are first-class objects.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Returning a nested function from an enclosing function includes the local variables of the enclosing function as the (non-local) lexical context of the returned function, yielding a closure.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Closures are frequently used in JavaScript, due to being used for callbacks.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] When creating a callback based on parameters, the parameters must be stored in a closure, otherwise it will accidentally create a closure that refers to the variables in the enclosing context, which may change.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Name resolution of properties of JavaScript objects is based on inheritance in the prototype tree—a path to the root in the tree is called a *prototype chain*—and is separate from name resolution of variables and functions.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Lisp dialects have various rules for scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] The original Lisp used dynamic scope; it was Scheme, inspired by ALGOL, that introduced static (lexical) scope to the Lisp family.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Maclisp used dynamic scope by default in the interpreter and lexical scope by default in compiled code, though compiled code could access dynamic bindings by use of `SPECIAL` declarations for particular variables.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] However, Maclisp treated lexical binding more as an optimization than one would expect in modern languages, and it did not come with the closure feature one might expect of lexical scope in modern Lisps.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] A separate operation, `*FUNCTION`, was available to somewhat clumsily work around some of that issue.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Common Lisp adopted lexical scope from Scheme, as did Clojure.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] ISLISP has lexical scope for ordinary variables.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] It also has dynamic variables, but they are in all cases explicitly marked; they must be defined by a `defdynamic` special form, bound by a `dynamic-let` special form, and accessed by an explicit `dynamic` special form.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Some other dialects of Lisp, like Emacs Lisp, still use dynamic scope by default.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Emacs Lisp now has lexical scope available on a per-buffer basis.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] For variables, Python has function scope, module scope, and global scope.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Names enter context at the start of a scope (function, module, or global scope), and exit context when a non-nested function is called or the scope ends.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] If a name is used prior to variable initialization, this raises a runtime exception.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] If a variable is simply accessed (not assigned to), name resolution follows the LEGB (Local, Enclosing, Global, Built-in) rule which resolves names to the narrowest relevant context.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] However, if a variable is assigned to, it defaults to declaring a variable whose scope starts at the start of the level (function, module, or global), not at the assignment.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Both these rules can be overridden with a `global` or `nonlocal` (in Python 3) declaration prior to use, which allows accessing global variables even if there is a masking nonlocal variable, and assigning to global or nonlocal variables.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Note that `x` is defined before `f` is called, so no error is raised, even though it is defined after its reference in the definition of `f`.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Lexically this is a forward reference, which is allowed in Python.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Assignment to a variable within a function causes it to be declared local to the function, hence its scope is the entire function, and thus using it prior to this assignment raises an error.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] This differs from C, where the scope of the local variable start at its declaration.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] The default name resolution rules can be overridden with the `global` or `nonlocal` (in Python 3) keywords.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] In the below code, the `global x` declaration in `g` means that `x` resolves to the global variable.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] It thus can be accessed (as it has already been defined), and assignment assigns to the global variable, rather than declaring a new local variable.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] Note that no `global` declaration is needed in `f`—since it does not assign to the variable, it defaults to resolving to the global variable.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] `global` can also be used for nested functions.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] R is a lexically scoped language, unlike other implementations of S where the values of free variables are determined by a set of global variables, while in R they are determined by the context in which the function was created.
[src:closure-conversion/lexical-scoping-p02] The scope contexts may be accessed using a variety of features (such as `parent.frame()`) which can simulate the experience of dynamic scope should the programmer desire.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] In computer programming, **name binding** is the association of a data or code entity with an identifier.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] An identifier bound to an entity is said to reference that entity.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] A machine language has no built-in notion of identifiers, but name-entity binding as a service and notation for the programmer is implemented by higher-level programming languages.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] Binding is intimately connected with scoping, as scope determines which names bind to which entities – at which locations in the program code (lexically) and in which one of the possible execution paths (temporally).
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] Use of an identifier id in a context that establishes a binding for id is called a binding (or defining) occurrence.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] In all other occurrences (e.g., in expressions, assignments, and subprogram calls), an identifier stands for what it is bound to; such occurrences are called applied occurrences.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] Rebinding should not be confused with mutation or assignment.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] *Rebinding* is a change to the *referencing* identifier.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] *Assignment* is a change to (the referenced) variable.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] *Mutation* is a change to an entity in memory, possibly referenced by a variable or bound to an identifier.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] The identifier `list` is bound to a variable in the first line; in the second, a linked list of strings is assigned to the variable.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] The linked list referenced by the variable is then mutated, adding a string to the list.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] Next, the variable is assigned the constant `null`.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] In the last line, the identifier is rebound for the scope of the block.
[src:closure-conversion/name-binding] Operations within the block access a new variable and not the variable previously bound to `list`.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] In computer programming, **variable shadowing** occurs when a variable declared within a certain scope (decision block, method, or inner class) has the same name as a variable declared in an outer scope.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] At the level of identifiers (names, rather than variables), this is known as name masking.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] This outer variable is said to be shadowed by the inner variable, while the inner identifier is said to *mask* the outer identifier.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] This can lead to confusion, as it may be unclear which variable subsequent uses of the shadowed variable name refer to, which depends on the name resolution rules of the language.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] One of the first languages to introduce variable shadowing was ALGOL, which first introduced blocks to establish scopes.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] It was also permitted by many of the derivative programming languages including C, C++ and Java.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] The C# language breaks this tradition, allowing variable shadowing between an inner and an outer class, and between a method and its containing class, but not between an if-block and its containing method, or between case statements in a switch block.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] Some languages allow variable shadowing in more cases than others.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] For example Kotlin allows an inner variable in a function to shadow a passed argument and a variable in an inner block to shadow another in an outer block, while Java does not allow these (see the example below).
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] Both languages allow a passed argument to a function/Method to shadow a Class Field.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] Some languages disallow variable shadowing completely such as CoffeeScript and V (Vlang).
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] The following Lua code provides an example of variable shadowing, in multiple blocks.
[src:closure-conversion/variable-shadowing] ECMAScript 6 introduction of `let` and `const` with block scoping allow variable shadowing.
